                                                                                                                                  Business Briefs

               
	 London, Jan. 6: The Tata group, which is the front-runner for acquiring British marquees Jaguar and Land Rover, is expected to appoint a senior executive of Ford Motors to run the two brands, The Sunday Times reported. The current chief executive is Geoff Polities, an Australian car industry veteran. It is understood that the Tatas plan few immediate changes to the businesses, with the uk operations and model plans kept intact, the report added.
              
	 New Delhi, Jan. 6: Rajeev Chandrasekhar, founder of bpl Mobile and chairman and CEO of financial firm Jupiter Capital, has been elected as the president of industry body Ficci for 2008. Chandrasekhar, who is also a member of Rajya Sabha, will take over from Wockhardt chief Habil Khorakiwala.
              
	 Dubai, Jan. 6: India Post and its counterpart in the UAE have entered into an agreement for a new system, called international express money order, that will allow faster money transfer between the two countries. The new system will be effective from February.
              
	 Mumbai, Jan. 6: jsw Steel will start the site work for the 10-million-tonne project in Bengal in the first week of February, a year after it had signed the development agreement with the state government. jsw Steel will invest Rs 35,000 crore in the project.
              
	 Mumbai, Jan. 6: Novartis will make a presentation to the Prime Ministers Office on selling over-the-counter medicines from post offices in rural areas to increase the industrys reach in villages.
                                                            
